tal Methods in the Study of Memory -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough still a relatively young field, memory studies has undergone significant transformations since it first coalesced as an area of inquiry. Increasingly, scholars understand memory to be a fluid, dynamic, unbound phenomenon—a process rather than a reified object. Embodying just such an elastic approach, this state-of-the-field collection systematically explores the transcultural, transgenerational, transmedial, and transdisciplinary dimensions of memory—four key dynamics that have sometimes been studied in isolation but never in such an integrated manner. Memory Unbound places leading researchers in conversation with emerging voices in the field to recast our understanding of memory’s distinctive variability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aAssmann, Aleida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBildt, Joyce van de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Lucy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCraps, Stef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraps, Stef, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrownshaw, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijck, José van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErll, Astrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnsrud, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c